PRIOR ART AND INSPIRATION
------------------------------------------------------------------------

AAEP draws conceptually and structurally from prior work in open
standards. The following projects influenced AAEP's design. AAEP does
not include or redistribute code from any of these projects unless
otherwise noted; the references are acknowledgments of intellectual
debt:

  • W3C Web Accessibility Initiative (WAI), Accessible Rich Internet
    Applications (WAI-ARIA) — for the model of a small, extensible
    vocabulary that bridges authors and assistive technology.
    https://www.w3.org/WAI/standards-guidelines/aria/

  • W3C Activity Streams 2.0 and ActivityPub — for the @context-based
    extension model and the use of JSON-LD for protocol payloads.
    https://www.w3.org/TR/activitystreams-core/

  • Model Context Protocol (MCP), Anthropic — for the contemporary
    pattern of standardizing how LLM applications connect to external
    capabilities, and as a complementary protocol that AAEP is
    designed to coexist with.
    https://modelcontextprotocol.io/

  • IETF RFC 9110 (HTTP Semantics) — for the discipline of separating
    a protocol's wire format from its transport and for the model of
    versioned, extensible specifications.
    https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9110

  • Microsoft Research, "From Struggle to Success: Context-Aware
    Guidance for Screen Reader Users in Computer Use" (CHI 2026,
    Chen et al.) — for establishing the research direction of
    LLM-mediated accessibility and motivating the need for the
    complementary infrastructure AAEP provides.
    https://arxiv.org/abs/2601.18092

  • IETF RFC 7807 / RFC 9457 (Problem Details for HTTP APIs) — for the
    pattern of structured, machine-readable error reporting reflected
    in AAEP's session.errored event.
    https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9457

